{
  "name": "hippocampal_circuit",
  "description": "Minimal hippocampus — episodic memory via auto-association. Real hippocampus: EC (entorhinal cortex, input) → DG (dentate gyrus, pattern separation via sparse coding) → CA3 (auto-associative memory, recurrent STDP) → CA1 (output, comparison with direct EC input). Our version: 2 RS entorhinal inputs project to 2 RS dentate gyrus cells. FS DG inhibition creates winner-take-all sparse coding (pattern separation — similar inputs get different DG representations). DG→CA3 via strong sparse 'mossy fiber' connections. CA3 has recurrent STDP connections (auto-association: patterns that co-occur get linked). CA3→CA1 via PLASTIC Schaffer collaterals. EC also projects directly to CA1 (temporoammonic path) for comparison. FS CA1 inhibition detects mismatch between CA3 recall and direct EC input (novelty signal). LTS interneuron provides sustained CA3 feedback inhibition. RS output integrates CA1. Implements: episodic memory encoding, pattern completion, pattern separation, novelty detection, context-dependent recall.",
